article.description:
Taquan Dean scored 18 points and Juan Palacios added 16 and 11 rebounds as the eighth-ranked Cardinals staggered through the first half before pulling away for a 78-61 victory against
Tennessee-Martin in the season opener for both teams.
article.headline: Louisville pulls away after tight first half
article.linkText: Louisville starts slow, but Pitino gets 450th win
article.story:
LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- For almost five months, while he recovered from a foot injury, Juan Palacios could do little but watch his teammates.

"I always wanted to play," he said.

He got his chance Saturday, finishing with 16 points and 11 rebounds in leading the (No. 8 ESPN/USA Today, No. 7 AP) Cardinals to a 78-61 victory over Tennessee-Martin 78-61 in the opener for both teams. Taquan Dean shot poorly but had 18 points, nine rebounds and five assists for Louisville.

The Cardinals play an exhibition game Sunday against NCAA Division II power Southern Indiana and are then off until Dec. 3.

The win was the 450th at the college level for Louisville coach Rick Pitino, who has also coached at Boston University, Providence and Kentucky.

Jeremy Kelly, who attended high school in Louisville, scored a career-high 31 points and grabbed nine rebounds for Tennessee-Martin, which finished 6-21 last season. Swingman Jared Newsom added 14 points.

Louisville went 33-5 and ended its season in the Final Four. The only returning starters were Dean and Palacios. The projected starting center, transfer David Padgett, sat out Saturday with a sprained left knee.

As a result, Pitino started one freshman, Terrence Williams, and one seldom-used sophomore, Terrance Farley, on the frontline. Williams had 11 points. Palacios, a 6-foot-8 sophomore forward, proved the stabilizing force.

"Without Tello," Pitino said, referring to Palacios by his nickname, "we would not have won. Experience wins over talent in college. We are lucky we got him back."

Dean was there on July 13 when Palacios landed wrong and damaged a ligament in his right foot while going up for an uncontested layup during a pickup game.

Palacios took the basketball court at his coach's urging early in the week before the season opener. It didn't take Palacios long to shake the rust: He played 30 minutes against the Skyhawks and far eclipsed his freshman per-game averages of 9.7 points and 6.5 rebounds.

"I've been working hard in the weight room even though I haven't been playing," Palacios said. "It's hurting a little. During the game with all the emotion I didn't feel it. It didn't bother me."

During the first half, when his teammates struggled from the field, Palacios scored 11 points to keep the Cardinals ahead. Louisville shot 9-for-33 in the first half, including 3-of-19 from 3-point range. But the long-range shots began falling after halftime; the Cardinals finished with 10 3-pointers in 33 attempts.

Louisville opened the second half on a 13-2 run, stretching a 5-point halftime lead to 44-28 with 16:12 left. Tennessee-Martin came no closer than eight points the rest of the way. Thanks to Kelly, who had five 3-pointers, the Skyhawks kept the game from becoming a blowout until the final minutes.

"I am glad we came back together after the run they went on [to start] the second half," Tennessee-Martin coach Bret Campbell said. "Give Louisville a lot of credit. They didn't shoot the ball well in the first half and when you go from 15 to 50 percent from 3-point range that is pretty good."
